  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Record of the Stream-side Pavilion at Ki Valley
  author: Lee Cham
  language: eng
  text: "East of Eagle City, a valley opens wide—three sides rise steep, while the south slopes gently down, resembling the shape of a winnowing basket. Thus we call it Ki Valley. Our eastern lands were once the domain granted to Ki Tzu, and they lie beneath the constellation of the Winnower in the heavens. That this valley bears the name of a basket is surely more than mere resemblance; the significance runs deeper still. For the basket is the instrument that separates and sifts, casting forth the chaff while gathering the grain—an image of the Supreme Harmony, where the noble remain within and the base are expelled without. Only the worthy can dwell in such a place; the unworthy would find no sanctuary here.\n\nMy noble friend, Minister Lee, has grown old in this valley. In the year of the Earth Dog, he built a pavilion by his dwelling. To the east he excavated a pond to watch the fish; he diverted the stream to raise his ducks. A thousand bamboo stalks he planted, standing in place of jade pipes and reeds; a hundred pine trees he set, to encourage integrity and virtue. These are the delights of his stream-side hall, the joys of the cultivated heart. Ascending the knoll to gaze afar, the Eagle Peak rises distant before him—is this not the heel of the basket? The waters of Lo flow across the foreground—are these not the winnower's tongue? Beyond, the broken hills and severed ravines stand like scattered pearls and scattered stars.\n\nHeaven holds the constellation of the Winnower; earth holds the Valley of Ki. The light of the stars and the vital energy of mountains answer one another, nurturing virtue and bestowing it upon the master of this stream-side pavilion. How else could Minister Lee have achieved such longevity and vigor? How else could his descendants flourish and multiply so abundantly? \n\nWhen I came to visit, he received me by the stream and offered wine, requesting that I compose a record of his pavilion. 'My hall has stood now for fifteen years,' he said, 'yet you are the first scholar of letters to grace these grounds. I beseech you to write its memorial.' I at first demurred with humble words. But days later he sent word again, his entreaties redoubled with such earnest warmth that I could not refuse."
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Ki Tzu (箕子): A legendary sage of ancient China who, according to Korean historical tradition, established a kingdom in the Korean peninsula after the fall of the Shang Dynasty.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The Winnower (箕): One of the Twenty-Eight Mansions of Chinese astronomy, represented as a winnowing basket, symbolizing both practical utility and moral discernment.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Supreme Harmony (泰卦): The Peace hexagram in the I Ching, representing heaven and earth in harmonious interaction.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The year of the Earth Dog (戊戍): Likely refers to 1418 CE in the Joseon dynasty calendar.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Eagle City (鷲城): A poetic reference to the location, possibly in the Chungcheong region of Korea.'
